This question was actually answered on 22nd March when the EU changed the leaving date (actually dates depending on outcomes) and these new dates were agreed by the UK are legally binding (in International law). The change to UK legislation is only required to put the UK law in compliance with international law and regardless of the UK carrying out the change the UK will not have left the EU on 29th March.
Nothing is agreed until everything is agreed.

This final prediction is based on the question not resolving until Parliament accepts the extension date but AND enacts May's deal. In this case this question becomes 1) UK revokes Article 50, pure and simple, 2016 referendum IS NOT honored. 2) The May deal is enacted, UK leaves the EU with a deal. 3) May deal fails leading to no deal Brexit, aka known as hard Brexit or crashing out of EU. 4) May deal fails and both UK and EU agree to a second extension not contingent on May deal. (This option may not be accounted for depending on criteria for what constitutes an extension.) 4) Hybrid approach, which is my preference and a likely outcome. May Deal is not considered or fails to pass. An emergency EU summit in which a new extension date, with different or no caveats for UK qualifying for extension is proposed, approved by EU, and this date is presented to Parliament which agrees AND ALSO agrees internally as to a plan forward that bypasses the May deal. This may require revocation to avoid unintended hard Brexit aka crash out, but with an internal agreement that Article 50 be invoked again after one or more of the following: 1) EU election is held and UK contingent is seated. 3) New UK snap election after 14 April. 2) New referendum. ( Mathematically, there is a fair way to do this by splitting the question AND asking a separate, new multiple choice question for type of Brexit v remain. Using weighted scores and using the higher of the first referendum leave vote or the second in weighting, it is possible to both give Brexit and remain an opportunity to prevail, while also providing Brexiteers the opportunity to both confirm their leave vote without risk AND give direction to the Government and Parliament to proceed towards a Hard Brexit, May's deal (which the EU has agreed to accept) or start over by writing new, different Article 50 invocation law which includes indications from the People and Parliament to guide the Government's UK negotiators toward a deal that is more likely to pass Parliament. And it avoids Brexiteers having the first referendum stolen by asking only a question that pits multiple forms of Brexit against one simple remain choice, which would guarantee failure for Brexit.

As the question has yet to resolve and is vague. I issued 2 predictions. One indicative of the question resolving by UK Parliament ratification of the extension, rather than it having resolved by UK requesting and receiving an extension which May claims that international law provided an extension upon EU vote. In which case this question HAS resolved. If on the other hand, if one holds that UK Parliament must now vote to extend the deadline and that the Macron/EU caveat that the 14 April extension date is contingent on the May deal be enacted by Parliament, then our greatest fear, an accidental crash out due to running out the clock resulting from ridgity and the application of a single binary approach to proposition before Parliament that has 3 or more possible outcomes. In other words May has to reach 50% on a question that at least 2 other major factions have separate & opposing motives to vote no on. The approach should have been splitting the question and entertaining indicative votes at the time of legislating the vote to invoke Article 50, an approach neither well suited to the UK parliamentary procedure nor Mrs May's character.

On may 21st, the Premier May accepted the agreement proposed by the EU 27 for an extension of the article 50. The UK Parliament has to approve or not the above-citedagreement: if it passes, the new deadline would be on the 22nd of May, increasing the possibility of implementing a new deal; if it fails the parliament has to choose between an extension till the 12 April or no extension, generating chaos about the siituation on the 29th of March. I think that the UK will take time to decide what to do, for sure until the 12 April and very likely also over the 22 of May. In both case, the UK would try to understand what to do, for example asking for further extension and negotiations, postponing that to very late 2019. They could also reconsider the option of a new referendum (we should remember there is a petition of more than 5 millions people to discourage Brexit), but again during this new extension period, and for sure not on the 29th of March, for the reasons I explained in my previous forecast. From the EU point of view, I think they neither have advantages from a no deal and would prefer to let the UK fix its domestic policy and decide how to procede: they agreed for the two possible extensions (12 april and 22 May), and I think they could go further. Indeed, even if it would be complicated and triggering including the UK in the European elections, the EU would prefer this option rather than a no deal.
Theresa May has been forced to ask the EU leaders to postpone this deadline on 21 March, now set at 12 April at the earliest. The article is therefore extended.

Considering the fact that the notification of Article 50 by the UK has been granted an extension at the point in time when I am forecasting (the 23rd of March) to the 12th of April, I will now answer the question considering the new extended deadline. The EU granted the three weeks extension on the condition that the UK needs to pass her Brexit deal on a third attempt. If the MPs approve May's deal, the EU will then extend the Brexit deadline further to the 22nd of May, thus giving the UK time to pass the required domestic legislation. The EU Parliament must also ratify the deal, but that’s expected to be mostly a formality. Because May was forced to ask for a delay in the deadline, there is a good chance that Brexit will be even further delayed. The delay creates a precedent, which is the reason why I give it an optimistic 35% likelihood. In this case of events, the Prime Minister comes up with a new plan in 3 weeks' time to move past the political paralysis which is already causing exasperation among other European leaders. However, the Parliament rejected May's plan by 230 votes in January and by 150 votes the second time, which is a massive margin to make up. It is still looking very likely that the Parliament will defeat the proposal once again.

It is now impossible for the UK to leave EU by 29th March with a deal, because no further vote on the WA is scheduled and even if a vote was won by the Government their is now insufficient time to pass the required legislation by 29th March. The only way that the UK could now leave the EU on 29th would be via a crash out "no deal", which MPs will be allow. A50 could be revoked to avoid a crash out and revoking would happening if the European Council refuses an extension. However the UK has asked for a "short extension" until 30th June and Tusk has said he would recommend a "short extension" if the UK parliament voted for the WA (Withdrawal Agreement that May has already agreed with the EU). it might only be until 22nd May rather than the 30th June (i.e before the EU elections, rather than May's date of before the new EU parliament sits) What Tusk did not say today was, what would happen if the UK parliament did not vote for the WA before 29th March. The reason for not saying now is probably that Mrs May has only asked for a "short extension" and the only reason was wanting it that she gave in her letter to Tusk, was to have another to get her WA passed by parliament. It is almost certain that if the UK parliament does not vote for the WA before the 29th March (and unless Mrs May can convince the Speaker that the WA is in some significant way different to the WA that parliament voted down last week, he will not allow Mrs May to even put it to parliament) Mrs May would need to do what she had previously said she was going to do, and sentdTusk another request to extend A50 for a period long enough to change the WA, and explain her plan for getting the WA changed (by a change of PM, a general election or referendum for example). Tusk did not say that he had ruled this option out. In my opinion putting pressure on MP to vote for May's WA in order to get an A50 extension will have little effect because may Conservative and DUP MPs say they would be happy to crash out of the EU, so they (say) that crashing out on 29th Match is better than May's WA.

(update) In my last forecast on this issue I was erroneously sure about the possibilty of a deal to extend the article 50's provisions. Given the last updates, I have to revise this certainty. The last scenario (Neither of the above will occur and the UK will leave the EU) comprehends both the possibility of a no deal Brexit and the possibility that the UK leaves the EU in the exact date given by the 2-years deadline set by Article 50. Both of these possible outcomes should be seriously taken into account, as Theresa May is facing major problems in making the Parliament accept the draft deal with the EU - rejected few days ago, https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47547887 - , and her journeys to find new deal could be not enough. On the other side, if the UK will find a last minute plan to proceed with the Brexit, the EU states claimed to be willing to extend the deadline (https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2019/mar/20/brexit-latest-news-letter-article-50-extension-pmqs-theresa-may-bends-to-pressure-from-tory-brexiters-and-rules-out-asking-for-long-article-extension-politics-live). Basically, the final outcome will depend on the next 9 days' May's ability to find a Brexit plan sustainable for the Parliament. I out a higher probability to the second scenario - extension - because I think the Parliament, the Government and the Prime Minister will find an agreement in the next days rather than to risk a no deal. Other sources: https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-32810887 for a comprehensive overview https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47355968 for a list of possibilities over when the Brexit can happen

Update Tuesday 19 March 2019 : New events are to be specified for the update of this forecast. Indeed, - The new (second) vote on the Brexit agreement was rejected by a large majority on 12 March. - The Speaker of the Parliament, John Bercow, said there will be no new vote on the Brexit agreement if the British government does not change the text (arguing an old parliamentary convention not used since 1912 ). But the European Union has repeatedly stated that the agreement will not be renegotiated. So we arrive at a "constitutional chaos" according to the Telegraph and The Guardian, which reinforces the uncertainty in the event. - Meeting at the European Summit on the 21st and 22nd of March where Theresa May will very probably ask for an extension of the deadline. However, the EU has warned that any extension must be duly justified and accepted unanimously by the 27. According to AFP, for France, an extension of the negotiations is "neither obvious nor automatic". Europeans want a "credible initiative" to avoid a divorce without agreement. Nathalie Loiseau, French Minister for European Affairs, said that "if no decision is made, the date of March 29 will fall, and it will be a non-agreement".

After having lost a second voting round on her Brexit deal and a failed attempt of putting her deal a third time on the table in the parliament, May is running out of options before her travels to Brussels on Thursday for an EU summit at which she has to request a postponement of the Brexit - as decided by a majority of the Britisch parliament. Because of that and the interest of the European Union to avoid a hard Brexit, the forecast at hand adapts its prediction towards a highly likely Extension of the negotiations - as of 85%. A 10% likelihood of a no deal Brexit is estimated to be left due to the fact that all member states have to agree upon the extension. A 5% chance that Brexit got stopped by the UK itself is estimated to be left due to the high degree of uncertainty around the issue, which is why self-critically no scenario should be excluded at this point of time.

The whole Brexit process is now becoming a farce or a constitutional crisis. You can choose which. The Speaker has just ruled that under a 400 year old rule Mrs May is not allowed to bring her EU Withdrawal Agreement motion back for a 3rd try to pass it unless it is substantially different to the one voted down last week. He has ruled that there were changes between the try in January and the try last week. The Solicitor General has said that Parliament may need to be prorogued to allow the motion to be reintroduced. (You can vote on the same thing in different sessions.) Clearly these action are against the spirit of the rules parliament, and show what a mess its in if these sorts of measures are being taken. Normal convention is that if a PM loses an important vote they resign. Its unprecedented for a PM to lose a vote by as much as Mrs May has done not to resign. Its obviously unprecedented for a PM to lose what is in effect two votes for the same thing to not resign. As far as I know no PM has ever tried to tried get around the rules by proroguing parliament (since 1948). This sort of behavour is not supposed to happen in the UK parliament. So whatever the outcome of this particular vote Mrs May will go down in history as the person who wrecked the traditional way of parliamentary behavior. The question is will any of this work for Mrs May? The current thinking is that even if May gets her WA motion voted on again, and even if the DUP suddenly decides that Mrs May deal is just what they always wanted and vote for it (any extra money for NI would, I am sure, not influence them at all) and some of ERG (hard Brexiteers) who it now seems don't really have any of their own principals, they will just follow what ever the DUP does, also vote for May's deal, Mrs May would probable still not get her deal through. Why would it get voted through? Brexiteers and Remainers are all agreed its a very bad deal, and Mrs May herself said "no deal is better than a bad deal", and hers is certainly a bad deal. Of course May could now threaten to just prorogue parliament until April so that it cannot change the A50 leaving date. That would set the constitution on fire! Its still almost 100% certain that A50 will be extended.

The instability posed from the internal quarrels in the Parliament give a basis for a growing destabilizing ambiguity over the set up date in March. This gives twofold opportunity for the politicians in power to promote the opinion of revoking Article 50, which would mean stopping Brexit in full. According to the European Court of Justice the decision to revoke Article 50 must be “unequivocal and unconditional”, contrary to its imposition. It seems to me that the chances to be revoked before 30th March, although possible, are relatively low. First, because it is 15th March already and in the Parliament talks about extension of the transition has already started following uncertain trade deal between UK and EU. The decision to revoke Article 50 needs to be unambiguious, which is not possible in the unearthed political situation in the UK, therefore in my view, I see a very high possibility and likelihood of prolonging the process of leaving for the UK due to the unsettled trade deal and the rest of business relations between the UK and EU. While I cannot claim certainty over what will occur in the future two weeks, it seems very unlikely for the last answer- neither a decisions to revoke, nor an extension, because this would leave the UK in a regulatory misbehavior in relation to the EU and it will further weaken its political power.

As of the 28 January amendment votes, it is now less likely that the Article 50 deadline will be extended. The passage of the Brady amendment to replace the backstop to prevent a "hard border" in Ireland with vague "alternative arrangements" conflicts with EU statements that the backstop is non-negotiable. The deadline cannot be extended unilaterally. The EU must agree and they must be given time to debate and vote. The rejection of the Spelman amendment requiring a vote whether or not to extend the deadline if May's "plan B" by 28 February makes extension less likely. Not having a date certain increases the likelihood of more postponements. More postponements increases the likelihood 'running out the clock' and an "accidental", "No Deal Brexit" — a prospect not entirely unwelcome in some quarters.

Britain’s House of Commons will vote on various Brexit measures today. Theresa May, the prime minister, still hopes to persuade MPs to back an amended version of the Brexit deal they rejected overwhelmingly two weeks ago. Some proposed amendments would constrain her government. One tries to stop Britain leaving the European Union without any deal on March 29th by requiring the government, if it has not passed a Brexit deal by February 26th, to ask the EU to extend the deadline. Others still ask Mrs May to renegotiate the Irish “backstop” to avert a hard border in Ireland, or even to scrap it by keeping the United Kingdom in a customs union with the EU. Yet the EU has said it cannot accept legal changes to the backstop. And extending the March 29th deadline requires all 28 EU members’ consent. Once again, what passes muster in Westminster could fail in Brussels, and vice versa.

Prime Minister Theresa May is backing a plan to ditch the most contentious part of her Brexit deal as she searches for a compromise all sides can support. In a meeting today, May effectively abandoned the agreement she's spent the past 18 months negotiating with the EU and threw the weight of her government behind a move to re-write the deal. She urged hundreds of Conservative politicians to support the proposal, which would strip out the so-called backstop plan for the Irish border, wrecking a compromise she's agreed to with the EU in the hope of securing one with her own party. Meanwhile, Sabine Weyand, the EU's deputy chief negotiator, warned of the risk of an accidental no-deal Brexit. "There's a very high risk of a crash out not by design but by accident," she said.

It is highly unlikely that the Article 50 notification will be revoked. With May surviving the no-confidence vote, as well as the estimated 22 weeks it would take to hold another referendum, the Brexit move remains firmly on the table. Now the question is; can the requisite negotiations take place before the 29 March deadline to make something happen? And will the EU budge on its conditions or reluctantly grant an extension? Though the EU has done their best to punish the UK for its decision throughout this entire process, ultimately their economies are too intertwined, which means they will likely grow slightly more lenient as the deadline approaches. I think it is most likely that they will come close to a deal as the deadline approaches, but grant an extension in order to finalize details and put a plan in place for execution. Less likely yet still possible, the UK will continue to be plagued with deadlock and the deadline will ultimately make the decision for them. Ultimately, however, a bad plan is better than no plan, and an extension will be needed to properly implement.

I believe it is highly unlikely that the UK will revoke their notification of Article 50. That would essentially invalidate the referendum that created BREXIT in the first place. In order to revoke Article 50, they'd have to take another referendum or risk a constitutional crisis, and a second referendum does not guarantee a different outcome.

The UK won’t revoke their submission of Article 50 without a new referendum. I believe a new referendum is unlikely. Extending Article 50 requires both UK and EU approval. The EU sees the Brexit issue as a UK problem, and has been uncooperative in finding a resolution. They are also unlikely to approve an extension unless they see a real tangible plan and not more of the “same ole, same ole.” Because a referendum is unlikely, the EU is not helping the UK work out its own domestic problems, and that a “no deal” will be disastrous to UK, the government will come together to make a deal happen, even if it’s a bad deal. Justifications below: May says Europe unlikely to extend Article 50; also says to do so would just prolong the Decision. In regards to another referendum, May and other parliamentarians (including some opposed to Brexit) say that a new referendum breaks down society’s confidence in the government and “shatter faith in democracy” – the people voted, and you should do a re-vote because the outcome is difficult. This leads me to believe that the government won’t allow a second referendum. However, a new referendum could be used as a last resort after all other options are exhausted. This is risky too because what if the new referendum results say “Yes, we the people still want Brexit?” and leaders have to consider that a referendum may not give them the answer they want. Let the clock wind down until 29 March could cause huge economic uncertainty for the British; however next meaningful vote won’t be until early Feb. Brussels says this is London’s decision, and they’re hands off. Based on news since the Brexit vote, the EU has never been happy about the Brexit decision, and have seemed uncooperative in helping London get to a decision, making it seem unlikely that the EU would approved an Article 50 extension, even if that’s what the UK wants. And an extension would require consent from all 27 member countries – 100% consensus on any issue is never easy. But yet, Yvette Cooper, the chairwoman of the home affairs select committee, is planning to put down a tightly worded amendment to give time for a bill that would give parliament the power to support an extension of article 50. Despite one of the worst defeats in Parliamentary history (voting down the Brexit deal), May survived a no-confidence vote. To me this implies the government wants to get to a solution – working out a new government would be devastating in Brexit process. Even the Britishers that don’t agree with May on her Brexit plans admire her grit and determination.

A punt either way. No way UK leaves EU while May is still in charge.

Its unlikely that May's Deal will be approved by Parliament as any one of four different groups who don't like her deal could vote against it and any one group would have enough votes to prevent the UK government passing the legislation. The four groups being; Hard Brexiteer (Conservatives), Hard Remain (Conservatives), Conservatives who are not happy that the "deal" contains no legally blinding framework for a Future Trade Deal (its only a Withdrawal Agreement), and the DUP. It seems very unlikely that the government would get sufficient opposition MPs to vote for May's Deal to get it passed. Its extremely unlikely that the parliament would allow the UK to just fall out of the EU with No Deal. Therefore that leaves the possibilities of stopping Brexit by revoking A50 or extending it. Revoking A50 is technically the easiest option because it does not require the EU to agree to it, it just needs the UK parliament to vote to Revoke. However Revoking A50 is politically much more difficult without parliament giving itself political cover by getting the UK public to agree by having a general election or referendum. There is not sufficient time to have a referendum between now and 29th March, (it has been calculated that a referendum would take a minimum of 22 weeks) and even if there was time to hold the actual referendum some time after the referendum and before 29th March would be required to take any actions that were necessary after the result was known (if the result of a referendum was that the Brexit process should continue but not with May's Deal then A50 would need to be extended to allow for more negotiations.) Its possible that a General Election could take place, but assuming that it did, it almost certain that the Prime Minister would either be May or Corbyn. If it were May then nothing much would have changed. If it were Corbyn and he wanted to negotiate a different Brexit deal there would not be time to do it before 29th March (assume no General Election could be called before the second half of January, which would give Corbyn about 4 weeks to negotiate a deal with the EU and get it approved. That seems almost impossible. The only possible deal I could see being done in that time would be to take May's Withdrawal Agreement, remove the Irish Backstop and replace it with a legally enforceable agreement that the UK will remain in the EEA and the Customs Union and will continue to contribute and obey EU rules and ECJ (i.e Norway+ Brexit). So extending A50 is by far the likely outcome. My interpretation of MPs comments and polling results (particularly the recent YouGov polls as interpreted by Peter Kellner) is that many Leave voters and most Brexit supporting MPs are losing confidence that any Brexit that resembles the version promised before the June 2016 referendum will ever be possible. Brexit was sold as having cake (a frictionless trade relationship with the EU) and eating it (being able to do FTAs with 3rd countries, without allowing EU citizen Freedom of Movement, without paying subs to the EU, and without having to follow the ECJ rulings). After two and half years of the EU telling the UK that to have frictionless trade you have to be a member of the EU (or EEA+ Single Market), which requires that you abide by EU rules including the Four Freedoms, pay contributions and follow rulling of the ECJ, even the Brexiteers are starting to realise the EU is not kidding. And most of the Brexiteers know full well that without frictionless trade much of the UK's manufacturing industry (the part that depends on trans-European supply chains) would migrate into the remaining EA (that's a much bigger market than the UK). While the Brexiteers favorite economist says that losing manufacturing is not a problem and that the UK could adjust, the Brexiteers are wondering how long it would take for this adjustment to happen (towns that lost their heavy manufacturing in the 1980s are still depressed now) and how the Leave voters will feel when they lose their jobs and are told to adjust. Leave voters are, I think, seeing that Brexit might be a great idea and a poke in the eye to the liberal elite, but the people that are likely be worse off are the left behind in the industrial towns, and maybe the elite (in the shape of the toffs who told them to vote Leave) have screwed them again. No one wants to admit they were wrong, so I think the Leave voters and the Brexiteer MPs are desperately hoping that someone else will stop Brexit, so they don't have have admit they were wrong voting to Leave. If someone else stops Brexit then the Brexiteers (and Leave voters) will be able to say that Brexit would have been a wonderful thing if only traitors had not stopped them getting the deal they imagined.

1. Revoking Art. 50 means staying in the EU. It is so risky an action for the UK executive to undertake that it is politically impossible. It would almost certainly require a parliamentary vote and would cause a constitutional crisis. Only pro-EU extremists would do this - and they are too far from political power to do so. See: https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-cancel-stop-revoke-article-50-explained-remain-stay-eu-latest-parliament-theresa-may-a8690886.html 2. Exending Art. 50 would be very difficult and would split, and severely weaken, governing Conservative Party. Current political dynamics and preparations be EU and UK government make extension of current arrangements after UK formally leaves and continuing negotiations much more likely if no WA ratified by UK Parliament. A vote in Parliament would almost certainly be required to extend Article 50. See: https://constitution-unit.com/2018/09/20/could-article-50-be-extended-to-allow-for-a-second-brexit-referendum/ I would like to assign 100% probability to neither 1. or 2. occuring but wanted to take into account 'known unknowns' and 'unknown unknowns'
